    padding: ${dt('menubar.base.item.padding')};
}

content.text:
I can see exactly what's happening visually, but the *why* contradicts everything in the code (the active layout config produces a single packed row, with no `justify-content` or width rule anywhere that would spread the nav full-width and bump it to its own line). I've traced it through PrimeNG's base CSS, the theme, and every app override without finding the culprit — so rather than ship a third blind guess, one quick console readout will pin it down exactly and let me fix it in one shot.

Could you paste this into your browser DevTools console (on the Item Library page) and share the output? It needs no rebuild:

```js
(() => {
  const pick = el => el && {
    tag: el.tagName + '.' + [...el.classList].join('.'),
    display: getComputedStyle(el).display,
    flexWrap: getComputedStyle(el).flexWrap,
    flex: getComputedStyle(el).flex,
    width: Math.round(el.getBoundingClientRect().width),
    justify: getComputedStyle(el).justifyContent,
    top: Math.round(el.getBoundingClientRect().top),
    bottom: Math.round(el.getBoundingClientRect().bottom),
  };
  const q = s => pick(document.querySelector(s));
  return JSON.stringify({
    toolbar: q('.toolbar'),
    nav: q('.vex-toolbar-nav'),
    navHost: q('vex-navigation'),
    menubar: q('.vex-menubar'),
    rootList: q('.p-menubar-root-list'),
    rightActions: pick(document.querySelector('.toolbar > div:last-of-type')),
  }, null, 2);
})()
```

The `top`/`bottom` values will tell me which elements are on which line, and the `flex`/`width`/`justify` values will reveal what's stretching the nav full-width. Once I see that, I'll know whether it's the menubar filling 100%, a flex-grow that's overriding my change, or a wrap on the toolbar — and fix the right thing immediately.

